    <!-- ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
    <!--  METHODS                                                    -->
    <!-- ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <para>
            <title>Trap design and deployment</title>
            Two novel low-cost subterranean pitfall trap designs were deployed
            at 10 sites across the Kalahari. The double-stratified design
            (trap line L01) captured invertebrates at two distinct soil depths
            (layers L01 and L02). The three-stratified design (trap line L05)
            captured invertebrates at three soil depths (layers L01, L02, and
            L03). Traps were checked approximately monthly, yielding five
            sampling occasions:
            Occasion 1 = October–November 2024,
            Occasion 2 = December 2024,
            Occasion 3 = January 2025,
            Occasion 4 = February 2025,
            Occasion 5 = March 2025.
          </para>
        </description>
      </methodStep>

      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <para>
            <title>Specimen identification and enumeration</title>
            Captured invertebrates were identified to the lowest practicable
            taxonomic level (Class, Order, Family, Subfamily, Tribe, Genus,
            Species). Counts (Number_caught) and dry biomass (Weight, in grams)
            were recorded per trap per collection event. Unidentified specimens
            at the Class level were excluded from all diversity and abundance
            analyses.
          </para>
        </description>
      </methodStep>

      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <para>
            <title>Statistical analyses</title>
            All analyses were conducted in R (≥ 4.x). The analysis script
            analyses_subterranean_submission.R reproduces the following:
            (1) Species richness (number of unique family–genus–species
            combinations) modelled with zero-inflated Poisson and negative
            binomial GLMMs (glmmTMB package), with site as a random effect
            and sampling occasion, macrohabitat (land_use), sand cover (Sand),
            and trap design (line) as candidate fixed effects.
            (2) Biomass modelled with Tweedie GLMMs (glmmTMB) using the same
            candidate predictors.
            (3) Abundance of Scarabaeidae and Tenebrionidae modelled jointly
            with Bayesian multivariate Poisson GLMMs (MCMCglmm package),
            with habitat and sampling occasion as fixed effects and site as
            a random effect; three parallel MCMC chains were run and
            convergence assessed via Gelman–Rubin diagnostics.
            Model comparison was based on AIC; sampling occasion was the
            primary driver of both richness and abundance.
          </para>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
    </methods>

